We know from the previous part of the question that

\[f'(x) = \frac{\cos x - \sin x}{e^x}\]

We take the derivative of $\displaystyle f'(x)$ to find:

\begin{align*}
f''(x) &= \frac{(-\sin x - \cos x)e^x - (e^x)(\cos x - \sin x)}{(e^x)^2} 
&= \frac{e^x (-\sin x - \cos x - \cos x + \sin x)}{(e^x)^2} 
&= \frac{-2\cos x}{e^x}
\end{align*}

Setting $\displaystyle f''(x)$ equal to zero to solve for possible
inflection points gives:

\[0 = \frac{-2\cos x}{e^x}\]

or, equivalently,

\[\displaystyle \cos x = 0\]

Using the unit circle we see that \emph{x = $\pi$/2} is the only solution in
$[0,\pi]$ of the equation $\cos(x) = 0$. This is our only possible point
of inflection, because $\displaystyle f''(x)$ is continuous everywhere.
Testing the values of $f''\left(\frac{\pi}2\right)$ with the second
derivative test gives:

:\{\textbar{} class=``wikitable'' \textbar{}- \textbar{}
\textbar{}\textbar{} $[0,\pi/2)$ \textbar{}\textbar{} $x = \pi/2$
\textbar{}\textbar{} $(\pi/2, \pi]$ \textbar{}- \textbar{}
$\displaystyle f''(x)$\textbar{}\textbar{} - \textbar{}\textbar{} 0
\textbar{}\textbar{} + \textbar{}- \textbar{} $\displaystyle f(x)$
\textbar{}\textbar{} concave down \textbar{}\textbar{} inflection point
\textbar{}\textbar{} concave up \textbar{}\}

Hence $\displaystyle f(x)$ has an inflection point at \emph{x = $\pi$/2}.
